The inevitability of death is important in both ‘The Charge of the Light Brigade’ and ‘The Destruction
of Sennacherib’. In the battle that Tennyson’s poem describes, British soldiers only had horses and swords,
while the Russians had guns and cannons, so they were charging towards certain death. Tennyson uses
repetition, such as in “Half a league, half a league, / Half a league onward”, to increase the poem’s pace and
drive it forward. The repeated, unvaried phrase suggests that there was no alternative but to keep charging
“onward”, and the reader feels hurried towards an inevitable conclusion, just like the soldiers were. Byron
uses anaphora to emphasise the inevitability of death in a similar way, as more than half of the lines begin
with “And”. This speeds up the poem and gives the reader the sense that all the sights (“rust”), sounds
(“gasping”) and sensations (“cold”) associated with death are taking place simultaneously. This creates a
sensory ‘wave’ that washes over both the Assyrians and the reader quickly — avoiding it seems impossible.
Answer Extract 1
The speakers in ‘The Charge of the Light Brigade’ and ‘The Destruction of Sennacherib’ both
describe conﬂict in the third person. Tennyson’s speaker looks over the “valley of Death” that the
sixhundred ride into and so can give descriptions of the “Cannon” blasts as they fall all around the
soldiers. This makes the conﬂict seem overwhelming — it surrounds the soldiers to the “right”, to the
“left” and “in front”. In Byron’s poem, the speaker’s distance lets them describe the effect of “the Angel
of Death” as it moves through the invaders, killing them all in a breath as “he pass’d”. The vivid scene
leaves the reader in awe, and makes the large-scale conﬂict appear destructive and spectacular.
Answer Extract 2
Both poets personify death to highlight the devastating effects of conﬂict. Tennyson’s personiﬁcation
of “Death” is given “jaws” which the soldiers ride into. This makes death seem predatory, and the image
of the soldiers being ‘gobbled up’ by the “mouth of Hell” emphasises the destructive effects of conﬂict.
In 1854, Christian ideals were more socially prominent, so this would have probably shocked Tennyson’s
readers more than modern readers. Byron also uses religious imagery to shock his readers through
the “Angel of Death”. An angel might be expected to save Sennacherib’s “cohorts”, but instead it makes
them all grow “still”. The positioning of “still” at the end of the stanza also gives a sense of ﬁnality, which
shows how permanent the effects of conﬂict are.
